            <section class="section">
                <h1 class="section-title"><span class="icon-holder"><i class="fas fa-user"></i></span>About me</h1>
                <div>
			<p>&ensp; 
			I always dreamed of becoming a scientist since I was young, but I never knew that I would develop a passion for earth science.
			In 2018, I was a junior undergraduate studying physics when I met Professor <a href="http://seismo.snu.ac.kr/people.html" target="_blank"><b>Junkee Rhie</b></a>, who introduced me to the science of earthquakes.
			I was soon intrigued by the inherently underdetermined problems in seismology, which required innovative ideas to take full advantage of the observations limited in both time and space.
			</p>
			<p>&ensp;During my Master's course, I numerically simulated the expected ground motions from large scenario earthquakes in the Korean Peninsula.
			I learned the limitations of kinematic rupture models, which often rely on ad-hoc constraints.
			Accounting for the earthquake model's physical plausibility (in terms of both validness and likelihood) may be the next problem in seismology that needs to be solved.
			</p>
			<p>&ensp; I am interested in constraining earthquake rupture processes through physics-based modeling and data-driven approaches, as a broad future research topic.
			I believe that characterizing the prior probability of the physically possible earthquake ruptures will enable accurate predictive earthquake modeling and efficient dynamic source inversion.
			With the importance of small-scale processes recently coming to light, an accurate description of the thermo-hydro-mechanical coupling in earthquake rupture process would be necessary.
			</p>
			<p>&ensp;I am currently searching for schools to apply for a Ph.D. course in Seismology/Geophysics. I am considering potential fields of study including, but not limited to: dynamic simulation, earthquake geodesy, field seismology, and computational seismology. </p> </div><!--//summary-->
            </section><!--//section-->

