            <section class="section" id="research">
                <h1 class="section-title"><span class="icon-holder"><i class="fas fa-briefcase"></i></span>Research Experience</h1>
		<div class="item"><div class="details"><p> &ensp;I perceive seismology as a study of identifying the mapping between the unknown earthquake source domain and the codomain of observables.
		Some aspects of the map remain unclear - the earthquake source process is not fully constrained, the observations are limited, and the mapping functions are restricted by our knowledge about the Earth's structure and the seismic wave propagation.
		I believe that the relationship between the source domain and the observable range should be formulated probabilistically to account for both epistemic and aleatory uncertainties.
		In this sense, my research aimed to make a small contribution towards identifying the mapping through statistical parametrization, albeit within a limited scope of frequency, magnitude, and region.</p>
		</div></div>

		<h2 class="sub-title">3-D Seismic Wave Propagation</h2>
		<div class="item">
			    <div class="details"><p>
		&ensp; In my first publication Lee et al. (<i>in press</i>), I simulated large (Mw>5.4) earthquake scenarios in the southeastern Korean Peninsula using a 3-D seismic velocity model and pseudo-dynamic source models within a <u><a href="https://geodynamics.org/cig/software/specfem3d/" target="_blank">SEM</a></u>-based framework.
		I used an ensemble of pseudo-dynamic rupture models generated by <a href="https://github.com/sgsong1017/SongRMG" target="_blank"><u>SongRMG</u></a> to 
		For more details, check out my presentation in AGU 2021!
				    
				    </p></div>
		    <a href="assets/data/Pseudo.png" target="_blank"><img src="assets/data/Pseudo.png" alt="" class="center"></a>

		    <div class="caption"><p> Gradient plots showing an example of a randomly generated pseudo-dynamic rupture model for a Mw 7.0 scenario.</p></div>

		    <a href="./assets/data/ResearchOverview.png" target="_blank"><img src="./assets/data/ResearchOverview.png" class="center"></a>

			<div class="caption">
			The spatial distribution of median PGV from the ground motion simulations of (a) Mw 5.4 pseudo-dynamic models in 3-D, (b) Mw 5.4 pseudo-dynamic models in 1-D, (c) <a href="https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/2017GL076960" target="_blank"><u>USFF model</u></a> in 3-D, and (d) USFF model in 1-D. The observed PGV values from the 2016 Gyeongju earthquake are plotted in circles. (Lee et al., <i>in press</i>)</div>
			
			<p>This study was an extension from my <a href="assets/data/InternReport.pdf" target="_blank">undergraduate intern research</a>, where I simulated the finite-fault models of large earthquakes in proximity from the <a href="http://equake-rc.info/srcmod/" target="_blank">SRCMOD</a> to validate the 3-D wave propgation simulations.
				    </p>


                </div><!--//item-->
                
                    <h2 class="sub-title">Seismic Hazard Assesment</h2>
		    <div class="item">
                    <div class="details">
                        <p>&ensp; I am currently trying to extend the results of physics-based ground motion simulations to probabilistic estimation of potential structural damage. This attempt is to transform a range in the observable space to . Applications involving the fragility curve in earthquake engineering may provide probabilistic predictions on slight, moderate, or extensive structural damage.</p> 
			<img src="assets/data/FaultFig.png" alt="" width=45% class="hp"><img src="assets/data/Hist.png" alt="" width=41% class="hp">

			<div class="caption">
				(Lee et al., <i>in preparation</i>)</div>
                    </div><!--//details-->
                </div><!--//item-->
                
                <div class="item">
			<h2 class="sub-title">Modeling Prompt Elastogravity Signals</h2>
                    <div class="details">
			    <p> &ensp; For my undergraduate thesis in Physics, I studied the numerical modeling of gravity perturbations induced by earthquake rupture.
			    This research topic was prompted by a coffee talk with my friend <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Taehun-Kim-11" target="_blank"><b>Taehun Kim</b></a>, who studies gravitational physics.
			    We were having a conversation about interdisciplinary projects, when he told me that the sensitivity of gravitational wave detectors were limited at low frequencies due to seismic noise.
			    I sensed a potential research topic and visited Professor <a href="https://physics.snu.ac.kr/en/research-faculty/faculty/fulltime?mode=view&profidx=5" target="_blank"><b>Sunghoon Jung</b></a> to discuss some ideas I had, which developed into this <u><a href="assets/data/PhysThesis.pdf" target="_blank">thesis paper</a></u> (<i>in Korean</i>).</p>
			<p>
			&ensp; Using the codes (by <u><a href="https://scholar.google.co.in/citations?user=o4ERK9UAAAAJ&hl=en" target="_blank">Surendra Somala</a></u>) implemented in the SPECFEM3D software, I calculated the transient variation of gravity acceleration during and after the earthquake rupture, which is caused by the volumetric deformation carried by P waves.
			I succesfully reproduced the results of <a href="https://academic.oup.com/gji/article/201/3/1416/763237" target="_blank"><u>Harms et al., (2017)</u></a>, which compared the numerical simulations of gravity perturbation with analytic solutions in homogeneous, elastic half-space.
			Although the application prospects of prompt gravity signals to early earthquake warning can be controversial, I find it meaningful that I have proactively searched and identified a unique interdisciplinary problem.
			</p>
		<a href="assets/data/Gravity.png" target="_blank"><img src="assets/data/Gravity.png" class="center"></a>
		<div class="caption"> The figure above illustrates the induced gravity acceleration vector at the Earth's surface, 5 seconds after a hypothetical Mw 6.5 earthquake at depth 50km.</div>
                    </div><!--//details-->
                </div><!--//item-->
                
            </section><!--//section-->
            
            <section class="section" id="field">
                <h2 class="section-title"><span class="icon-holder"><i class="fas fa-archive"></i></span>Field Experience</h2>
		<div class="item">
			<img src="assets/data/Field.jpg" alt="" width="28%" class="hp">
			<div class="details">
				<p> &ensp;  The contrast between tabletop data analysis and outdoor fieldwork is another charm of seismology. I have participated in research projects deploying broadband seismometers and geophone arrays at various sites in the Korean Peninsula. 
				I am familiar with the broadband seismometer <u><a href="https://www.nanometrics.ca/products/seismometers/trillium-compact" target="_blank">Trillium Compact</a></u>, the digital recorders <u><a href="https://www.nanometrics.ca/products/digitizers/centaur-digital-recorder" target="_blank">Centaur and Taurus</a></u>, and the geophone <u><a href="https://smartsolo.com/igu-16hr-3c/" target="_blank">SmartoSolo IGU-16HR 3C</a></u>.
				The acquired data are currently being used by the lab members for their research.</p>
				<li>Ulleung Island, South Korea (<i>Jul 2021</i>)</li>
					<li>Hallasan Mountain, Jeju Island, South Korea (<i>Oct 2020 - May 2021</i>)</li>
					<li>Yeoncheon County, South Korea (<i>Nov - Dec 2020</i>)</li>
			</div></div>
